05:36.636 --> 05:41.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The death by poisoning of a
former Russian spy in London was
thrust back into the headlines

05:41.074 --> 05:45.779 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
today, as a British inquiry into
his killing released its report.

05:45.779 --> 05:50.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Alexander Litvinenko fled Russia
nearly 20 years ago and accused
the former chief of

05:50.951 --> 05:56.256 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Russia's spy agency,
now-President Vladimir Putin, of
corruption. In 2006, he met two

05:56.256 --> 06:00.560 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russian spies at a London hotel,
and three weeks later, he was
dead.

06:00.560 --> 06:03.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chris Ship of Independent
Television News begins our
coverage.

06:03.763 --> 06:08.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS SHIP: We were reminded
today that the radioactive
poison inside Alexander
Litvinenko's

06:08.668 --> 06:14.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
body was so strong, he had to be
buried in a lead-lined coffin.
Today, the Russian security

06:14.374 --> 06:19.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
service the FSB was blamed for
his killing. And the orders,
concluded the man who led

06:19.446 --> 06:23.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the inquiry, most likely came
from the top, the very top, he
said.

06:23.783 --> 06:29.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SIR ROBERT OWEN, Litvinenko
Inquiry Chairman: The operation
to kill Mr. Litvinenko was
probably

06:29.756 --> 06:40.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
approved by Mr. Patrushev, then
head of the FSB, and also by
President Putin.

06:40.934 --> 06:45.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS SHIP: The FSB agents did
it by pouring a deadly
substance, polonium-210, into
this

06:45.872 --> 06:49.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
teapot from which Mr.
Litvinenko was drinking.

06:49.809 --> 06:54.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This was him in a hotel lobby a
few moments before the meeting.
He took just three or

06:54.414 --> 06:59.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
four sips of tea, he later told
police, but after he'd left the
hotel, the radiation had

06:59.052 --> 07:02.789 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
already started to
spread through his body.

07:02.789 --> 07:08.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the inquiry, the poisoning in
a meeting room at the hotel here
was referred to as

07:08.561 --> 07:13.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a mini-act of nuclear terrorism
on the streets of London. And
because the orders likely came

07:13.967 --> 07:17.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from the Kremlin, Mr.
Litvinenko's widow has demanded
today the strongest possible
response

07:17.871 --> 07:20.507 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from the British government.

07:20.507 --> 07:25.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARINA LITVINENKO, Widow of
Alexander Litvinenko: It's time
for David Cameron. I'm calling
immediately

07:25.378 --> 07:31.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for complete expulsion from the
U.K. of all Russian intelligence
operatives.

07:31.084 --> 07:35.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SHIP: Later, she told me
she hopes justice would catch up
with President Putin.

07:35.955 --> 07:39.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARINA LITVINENKO: Yes, we know
not all dictators exist forever,
and, one day, you need to answer

07:39.626 --> 07:41.761 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for everything, what you did.

07:41.761 --> 07:45.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THERESA MAY, British Home
Secretary: This was a blatant
and unacceptable breach of the

07:45.465 --> 07:50.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most fundamental tenets of
international law and of
civilized behavior.

07:50.570 --> 07:55.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SHIP: If there was any
doubt Litvinenko was a target of
the Russian state, watch this

07:55.475 --> 08:01.014 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
video of Russian special forces
in training, their target,
Alexander Litvinenko.

08:01.014 --> 08:06.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the man accused of the
poisoning, Andrei Lugovoi, now,
by the way, a senior Russian

08:06.419 --> 08:11.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
politician, said today, "The
accusations against me are
absurd and once again confirm
London's

08:11.458 --> 08:15.161 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
anti-Russian stance."

08:15.161 --> 08:19.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nothing from President Putin
himself today, but Britain's
reliance on him in the fight

08:19.666 --> 08:24.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
against I.S. in Syria may
limited the U.K.'s response for
a murder which turned this man

08:24.637 --> 08:28.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
into this one days
before his death.

08:28.007 --> 08:32.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: We dig deeper
into the story with Michael
McFaul, U.S. ambassador to
Russia

08:32.379 --> 08:37.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from 2012 to 2014. He's now a
professor at Stanford
University. And Steven Lee
Myers,

08:37.951 --> 08:41.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he covers foreign affairs and
national security at The New
York Times. He was based in
Russia

08:41.521 --> 08:46.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from 2002 to 2007. He's also the
author of "The New Tsar: The
Rise and Reign of Vladimir

08:46.159 --> 08:48.128 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Putin."

08:48.128 --> 08:53.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Steven Lee Myers, I want to ask
you first, who was this
individual that was killed?

08:53.199 --> 08:58.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN LEE MYERS, The New York
Times: Alexander Litvinenko was
a fairly obscure intelligence

08:58.738 --> 09:05.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
officer in the KGB and then
later the FSB in the '90s,
wasn't very well-known until

09:05.278 --> 09:11.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he very sensationally came
forward with accusations that
the unit that he worked for was
involved

09:11.451 --> 09:15.021 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in corrupt activities and in
fact an assassination plot.

09:15.021 --> 09:19.459 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When he came forward at the time
-- this was in 1998 -- the
director of the FSB at the

09:19.459 --> 09:23.463 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
time, the federal security
service, was Vladimir Putin.

09:23.463 --> 09:27.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Steven,
staying with you for a second,
in your reporting at the

09:27.834 --> 09:32.138 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time, a lot of people suspected
this. What did we learn today
from this report?

09:32.138 --> 09:36.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN LEE MYERS: You know,
people who followed this
inquiry, which really was an
extraordinary

09:36.309 --> 09:43.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
process, might not be that
surprised by the conclusions
that were in it.

09:43.183 --> 09:49.355 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think the tone of it and
the accusation linking it,
though, with a caveat, to the

09:49.355 --> 09:55.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kremlin and Putin himself is
really what was so striking, to
see all these facts laid out.

09:55.295 --> 09:59.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A lot of what was known about
this case dates back to the
investigation that happened in

09:59.799 --> 10:03.102 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
2006 and 2007.

10:03.102 --> 10:08.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when the British originally
charged the two suspects, you
know, many of the details

10:08.441 --> 10:12.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were you know, many of the
details were already known at
that time, but I think that
there

10:12.111 --> 10:17.784 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was an eagerness inside the U.K.
especially to learn more about
this case and who did

10:17.784 --> 10:24.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
order it, and, you know, the
judge's report today took that
to the top of the Kremlin.

10:24.023 --> 10:26.526 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Michael
McFaul, does this change your
understanding of the events?

10:26.526 --> 10:31.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL, Former U.S.
Ambassador to Russia: No.

10:31.064 --> 10:35.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I, too, like Steven, have
followed this case for a long
time both as an academic and
then

10:35.668 --> 10:40.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the government. I have only
had a chance to skim the entire
report. I haven't read

10:40.740 --> 10:44.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
everything, but I have read the
conclusions closely, and I want
to applaud them for doing

10:44.944 --> 10:50.049 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
this. I think it's very
important, even if nothing more
comes of it, that somebody went

10:50.049 --> 10:56.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the trouble to document all
this for history and so that
this has been recorded.

10:56.222 --> 11:02.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Having looked at it, there is no
new smoking gun. There is no
secret tape that recorded

11:02.695 --> 11:07.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Putin giving the order or Mr.
Patrushev giving the order, but
it just puts together the
circumstantial

11:07.734 --> 11:12.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
evidence, which is to say that
these two agents came from
Moscow.

11:12.872 --> 11:17.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They had polonium, something you
can't just buy on the streets.
They poisoned him. They

11:17.510 --> 11:20.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
went back to Moscow and they
have been protected by the
Russian state ever since. In
fact,

11:20.880 --> 11:25.718 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Mr. Putin has given Mr.
Lugovoi a state award.

11:25.718 --> 11:29.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's based on that, that
they come to their conclusions,
and it's pretty damning

11:29.789 --> 11:34.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conclusions, therefore, for both
President Putin and at the time
the head of the FSB,

11:34.360 --> 11:37.096 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Mr. Nikolai Patrushev.

11:37.096 --> 11:42.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Steven Lee
Myers, does this almost bolster
Putin's image as a tough guy,

11:42.602 --> 11:46.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as someone that get things done,
even having this out there?

11:46.072 --> 11:50.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN LEE MYERS: I don't think
anybody inside the Kremlin
welcomes this kind of attention

11:50.944 --> 11:56.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or the accusations which again
have been out there the last 10
years.

11:56.082 --> 12:01.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have vigorously fought
them. Putin doesn't want to be
portrayed as somebody who would

12:01.187 --> 12:07.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
carry out this kind of attack,
ordering this kind of
assassination. That said,
Litvinenko

12:07.594 --> 12:12.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was widely reviled in the
Russian elite, especially among
the security services.

12:12.699 --> 12:17.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And even in the testimony that
is included in the report today,
one of the suspects said

12:17.370 --> 12:21.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the killing was meant to
send a message to others who
might betray their oath to the

12:21.007 --> 12:23.643 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
state in Russia.

12:23.643 --> 12:26.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Michael
McFaul, I see you agreeing
there. This was a killing that
was

12:26.212 --> 12:30.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
meant to send a message by
that slow, painful death?

12:30.083 --> 12:36.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Oh, absolutely.
I mean, he was a traitor.
Remember, he worked for the

12:36.289 --> 12:42.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
