organizations that Mr. Putin and
Patrushev worked for.

12:42.061 --> 12:47.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He then defected. He then made
these claims -- that's in the
report again -- that the

12:47.133 --> 12:54.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FSB orchestrated terrorist
attacks against Russian citizens
back in the fall of 1989

12:54.273 --> 12:58.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as a way to rally Russians
around the flag and support
ultimately President Putin. That

12:58.578 --> 13:01.414 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
was the first time that
he ran for president.

13:01.414 --> 13:06.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So there's no doubt that they
hated him. They made that very
clear. And they were sending

13:06.019 --> 13:10.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a signal. And I want to point
out, there's been a lot of
assassinations, there's been

13:10.823 --> 13:17.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a lot of killings. Just last
year, the leading figure of the
opposition, Boris Nemtsov, was

13:17.330 --> 13:22.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
murdered, assassinated just a
few feet from the Kremlin walls,
again, with all this ambiguous

13:22.368 --> 13:27.173 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
notion, actually who
ordered it, who didn't.

13:27.173 --> 13:31.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's a pattern. It's not
just a one-off. And the last
thing I want to remind you of,

13:31.978 --> 13:38.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
even if they didn't make these
calls, right, even if somehow
this was a rogue operation,

13:38.818 --> 13:43.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's also pretty damning. That
means that President Putin is
not in charge of his state

13:43.589 --> 13:48.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and that people within the
regime can carry out
assassinations without his
blessing. That's

13:48.294 --> 13:52.598 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
also not a very good message
about his control within Russia.

13:52.598 --> 13:55.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Steven, what's
the response been from Russia
today?

13:55.368 --> 13:59.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN LEE MYERS: You know, as
you would expect, and as it has
been from the very beginning,

13:59.806 --> 14:05.278 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
they have denounced this
investigation. They say that the
accusations that the Russian

14:05.278 --> 14:10.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
state was involved at all is
part of a politically motivated
smear campaign against Russia
and

14:10.516 --> 14:13.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
against Putin himself.

14:13.986 --> 14:21.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you know, it's hard for
them, I think, in Russia to
understand this or accept this

14:21.260 --> 14:25.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as an independent inquiry. They
say the whole thing was
politicized to come to a
predetermined

14:25.665 --> 14:27.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
conclusion.

14:27.533 --> 14:31.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally,
Michael McFaul, what about the
diplomatic consequences of

14:31.871 --> 14:35.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this? The U.K. and the U.S. are
kind of in a delicate dance with
Russia right now, especially

14:35.608 --> 14:38.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
when it comes to Syria.

14:38.244 --> 14:44.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Well, I think
for Prime Minister Cameron, it's
going to be very difficult,

14:44.383 --> 14:51.591 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because they took years to get
over this big interruption in
their bilateral relationship.

14:51.591 --> 14:55.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they were just slowly
creeping towards a better
relationship when I was
ambassador,

14:55.328 --> 14:59.065 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and then the invasion of
Ukraine set that back.

14:59.065 --> 15:03.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're now in this moment, as you
just noted, of trying to
cooperate with Russia on Syria,

15:03.536 --> 15:08.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
both on a political solution,
but also on the fight against
ISIS. And, therefore, I

15:08.241 --> 15:13.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think they're going to try to do
damage control. That would be my
prediction.

15:13.980 --> 15:15.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Michael McFaul, Steven Lee
Myers, thanks so much.

15:15.782 --> 15:18.251 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVEN LEE MYERS: Thank you.

15:18.251 --> 15:26.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MCFAUL: Thank you.

15:26.492 --> 15:32.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The crowded
Republican field running for
president faces the first real

15:32.698 --> 15:37.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
test in less than two weeks,
when voting begins in Iowa and
New Hampshire.

15:37.069 --> 15:39.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senator Rand Paul of Kentucky is
hoping young people show up in
big numbers and help him

15:39.972 --> 15:42.141 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
stand out.

15:42.141 --> 15:45.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Gwen Ifill sat down with him
earlier today as part of our
Running series.

15:45.845 --> 15:48.848 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Senator Paul, thank
you so much for joining us.

15:48.848 --> 15:49.382 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SEN. RAND PAUL (R-KY),
Presidential Candidate: Thanks
for having me.

15:49.382 --> 15:50.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It seems like
the longest race ever.

15:50.016 --> 15:51.717 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

15:51.717 --> 15:54.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And here we are,
about two weeks out before the
first voting in Iowa and then

15:54.086 --> 15:57.023 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in New Hampshire.

15:57.023 --> 16:01.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Donald Trump is surging. Ted
Cruz is surging. How do you
assess the race today?

16:01.227 --> 16:04.530 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. RAND PAUL: I think a lot
will be told the night of the
election.

16:04.530 --> 16:09.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think, in some ways, this
is the first election I have
really seen led so much by

16:09.502 --> 16:14.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
polling. And I think polling is
getting more and more inaccurate
over time, because more

16:14.207 --> 16:18.077 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and more people are on cell
phones and not really included.
A lot of our support comes

16:18.077 --> 16:21.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from younger voters, college-age
voters. And I have yet to meet a
college student who has

16:21.347 --> 16:23.950 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ever been included in a poll.

16:23.950 --> 16:28.054 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think we have to wait and
see how the voters vote. We have
a really good ground

16:28.054 --> 16:33.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
game. Our goal is to get 10,000
students to vote in Iowa.
They're in school for the first

16:33.960 --> 16:38.097 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
time in several presidential
election cycles, so we think we
have a real shot.

16:38.097 --> 16:41.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, explain to me a
little bit more how you do that
in Iowa and how you duplicate

16:41.367 --> 16:44.036 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something like that if you
need to in New Hampshire.

16:44.036 --> 16:47.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. RAND PAUL: President Obama
did very well with students, and
he won the student vote

16:47.506 --> 16:50.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
probably 3-1, and he energized
them and got them out.

16:50.309 --> 16:54.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have been doing a lot of the
same thing, working in dorms, on
campus, really trying

16:54.680 --> 16:59.118 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to organize dorm by dorm, get
the kids out. We think a lot of
these students aren't wedded

16:59.118 --> 17:04.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to one party or another yet. But
they're interested in being left
alone.

17:04.056 --> 17:08.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And part of the theme of my
campaign is, the government
ought to leave people alone. The

17:08.561 --> 17:12.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
government ought shouldn't be
collecting everyone's phone
records. I think young people,
their

17:12.064 --> 17:14.200 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
life revolves
around their phone.

17:14.200 --> 17:18.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If I want to talk to my kids and
they're in the basement, I have
to send them a text to

17:18.204 --> 17:22.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
talk to them sometimes. And I
think that they understand as
much or more than anybody else

17:22.341 --> 17:25.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the government really
shouldn't have access to all
their records.

17:25.144 --> 17:28.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And when they pick
up their phones and they want to
look up political news, they

17:28.414 --> 17:30.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
yesterday only read about
Sarah Palin and Donald Trump.

17:30.950 --> 17:32.585 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

17:32.585 --> 17:34.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Sucks all the air
out of the room, including on
those little devices.

17:34.020 --> 17:35.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SEN. RAND PAUL: Yes.

17:35.321 --> 17:37.556 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: How do you
break through that?

17:37.556 --> 17:40.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. RAND PAUL: Maybe not quite
as bad as you would think,
because young people aren't

17:40.559 --> 17:43.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really watching the traditional.
They're getting things from
their friends. They're getting

17:43.062 --> 17:46.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
things passed around that
are funny or humorous.

17:46.132 --> 17:51.137 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they're not really wedded to
the cable news so much. And I
think it is a disservice,

17:51.137 --> 17:56.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
though, that the news, I think,
has really dumbed the whole
thing down, because it's

17:56.409 --> 18:00.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been a nonstop Trump circus for
months and months now. If you
add up all the coverage

18:00.646 --> 18:04.250 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of all the other candidates,
he's getting 25 times more.

18:04.250 --> 18:08.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, is it any surprise that he's
leading in the polls? Which came
first? Was he leading

18:08.788 --> 18:13.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the polls or the coverage?
It's been a little bit of both.
But I think it's a disservice

18:13.926 --> 18:18.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really to the country and to
getting a serious debate,
because, see, I think it's
important

18:18.030 --> 18:22.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to know who's going to be in
charge of the nuclear weapons.

18:22.301 --> 18:26.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump doesn't seem -- in the
last debate, the CNN debate, he
didn't seem to understand

18:26.372 --> 18:31.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what the nuclear triad was, that
we have land missiles, sea and
air. And then a week after

18:31.877 --> 18:35.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the debate, his campaign was
asked, and they said, well, yes,
we knew about nuclear weapons,

18:35.481 --> 18:40.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and our problem is we haven't
been willing enough to use
nuclear weapons.

18:40.586 --> 18:43.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's a pretty profound and
scary thought, that we would
have someone running who thinks

18:43.990 --> 18:46.158 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we need to use our
nuclear weapons more.

18:46.158 --> 18:47.426 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Which used to
be a disqualifying thing.

18:47.426 --> 18:48.594 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SEN. RAND PAUL: You would think.

18:48.594 --> 18:50.696 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: But it doesn't
seem like that this year.

18:50.696 --> 18:55.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seems that you have said
Donald Trump would destroy the
party. You have said that Ted

18:55.735 --> 19:00.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Cruz is not authentic. Yet, none
of that seems to -- none of
those criticisms, at least for

19:00.006 --> 19:02.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you, seem to grab on.

19:02.508 --> 19:05.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. RAND PAUL: Well, I think we
have simplified the debate too
much and we have made it all

19:05.644 --> 19:10.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about, well, we're just going to
show -- there was -- I bet you,
of the eight or 10 hours

19:10.616 --> 19:14.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that people were awake yesterday
they could watch the news that
Trump was on probably

19:14.687 --> 19:17.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the majority of the time, maybe
80 to 90 percent of the news
cycle, all day long, repeated

19:17.857 --> 19:19.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
over and over again.

19:19.859 --> 19:24.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And as a consequence, we're not
breaking through to think about.
And I have made the point

19:24.263 --> 19:29.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is, is that the difference
between Trump and myself is,
Trump wants power. And he thinks

19:29.001 --> 19:33.439 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he's so smart that he will fix
everything in the country; just
give him power.

19:33.439 --> 19:38.444 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I understand the corrupting
influence of power and that it
is our American tradition

19:38.444 --> 19:43.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to worry about having too much
power to gravitate to any
person, and that I want more
power

19:43.182 --> 19:46.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be dispersed among the states
and the people, and that I want
the power in Washington to

19:46.819 --> 19:49.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
be constrained by
the Constitution.

19:49.855 --> 19:53.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's a completely different
tradition. But I think there
could be an intellectual debate

19:53.826 --> 19:58.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about which is the better
proposition, give one person all
of the power and let them fix

19:58.230 --> 20:01.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the country, or acknowledge that
maybe power has a corrupting
influence.

20:01.534 --> 20:05.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: An intellectual
debate sometime in the next two
weeks.

20:05.438 --> 20:08.774 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Depending on the turnout of
young people, who we don't know
if they would turn out for

20:08.774 --> 20:12.244 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something like an Iowa caucus --
sounds like a tough proposition.

20:12.244 --> 20:16.182 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEN. RAND PAUL: It may be. But
we're working very hard. We have
1,000 precinct chairs in

20:16.182 --> 20:19.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Iowa. I think that's more than
anyone else has announced.

20:19.852 --> 20:24.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We announced last week when I
was there that we had made
500,000 phone calls. That's an

20:24.356 --> 20:27.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enormous project. So, we have
put a lot of work and effort in
it. We will know February

20:27.593 --> 20:30.429 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
1 whether it works or not.

20:30.429 --> 20:34.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think I guess what's
disappointing to us is that
people think that the election

20:34.333 --> 20:36.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is already over, it's been
pre-decided. And we haven't even
started. We haven't even had

20:36.535 --> 20:38.838 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
one vote yet.

20:38.838 --> 20:42.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, that's been
written, especially about your
campaign. And you weren't on the

20:42.007 --> 20:44.877 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
debate stage last weekend. And
that raised that question.

20:44.877 --> 20:51.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I looked at this. And I do
wonder what your grand plan is,
especially -- you have

20:51.217 --> 20:54.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
got a lot of endorsements in New
Hampshire. As you point out, you
have a lot of endorsements

20:54.753 --> 20:58.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Iowa. One endorsement like
Sarah Palin seems to blow all
that out of the water.

20:58.691 --> 21:00.659 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
SEN. RAND PAUL:
Maybe, maybe not.

21:00.659 --> 21:04.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
See, I still think there is a
question of whether Donald Trump
is a conservative. He

21:04.864 --> 21:08.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spent most of his life as a
progressive Democrat. He was
pro-choice for the vast majority
of

21:08.968 --> 21:13.606 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
life -- of his life, and now
he says now he's pro-life.

21:13.606 --> 21:17.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, really, some of the things
that really energize
conservatives -- when the Tea
Party

21:17.143 --> 21:21.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
movement arose, one of the
things that we were very annoyed
with was bailing out the

21:21.213 --> 21:24.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
big banks, that the middle class
shouldn't have to bail out the
big banks in New York,

21:24.316 --> 21:27.419 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and yet Donald Trump
supported that.

21:27.419 --> 21:33.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Most of us were opposed to
centralizing the control of
health insurance and health in

21:33.058 --> 21:37.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
our country, and the idea that
there would be a single-payer
was something that really

21:37.596 --> 21:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was the opposite of what we
believed in. And he's been for
that as well.

21:41.500 --> 21:45.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, really, there are a lot of
things about Donald Trump that
aren't conservative, his

21:45.204 --> 21:49.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
belief in eminent domain, that
the government should take
private property from one
property

21:49.875 --> 21:53.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
owner, and give it to Donald
Trump, basically, for a casino.
That goes against what most

21:53.445 --> 21:55.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
conservatives believe.

21:55.814 --> 21:59.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Let's talk about
what you believe. You are not
pro-war, anti-war, I think is

21:59.618 --> 22:01.320 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
fair to say, in a
libertarian sense.

22:01.320 --> 22:03.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SEN. RAND PAUL: Right.

